item.title: 6 January 2014: “Aitzaz has made us proud by valiantly intercepting the bomber and saving the lives of hundreds of his fellow students.”
item.description: On 6 January 2014 at Government High School Ibrahimzai, a school in Ibrahimzai, Hangu, in northwestern Pakistan, 15-year-old student Aitzaz Hassan stopped a suicide bomber, who detonated his explosives, killing himself and Aitzaz.  The young hero’s father, Mujahid Ali Bangash, said, “Aitzaz has made us proud by valiantly intercepting the bomber and saving the lives of hundreds of his fellow students. I am happy that my son has become a martyr by sacrificing his life for a noble cause.” Mr. Bangash, who works in the United Arab Emirates, added, “Many people are coming to see me but if they try to express sympathy, I tell them to congratulate me instead on becoming the father of a martyr. I will be even more than happy if my second son also sacrifices his life for the country.”  Mudassar Hassan Bangish, Aitzaz’ cousin, said, “My cousin sacrificed his life saving his school and hundreds of students and school fellows. The suicide bomber wanted to destroy the school and school students. It was my cousin who stopped him from this … destruction.”  Mr. Bangish heard from witnesses at the school what had happened. He said that Aitzaz noticed the suicide bomber, who was wearing a school uniform and a suicide vest, and that Aitzaz’ friends did not want him to confront the suicide bomber: “So he told them, ‘I’m going to stop him. He is going to school to kill my friends’. He wanted to capture this suicide bomber. He wanted to stop [him]. Meanwhile the suicide bomber blasted himself which resulted in the death of my cousin.”  Aitzaz stopped the suicide bomber at the gates to the school, and the suicide bomber detonated the explosives. Aitzaz died in a hospital following the explosion. Most of the students at the school are Shiite. Writer and journalist Omer Aziz tweeted, “Aitzaz Hasan, 15 years old, gave his life to stop a suicide bomber in Pakistan. A reminder to us all what real courage is. RIP, brave soul.” Mr. Bangash said, “My son made his mother cry, but saved hundreds of mothers from crying for their children.” According to District Police Officer (DPO) Iftikhar Ahmad, student Aitzaz Hasan “laid down his life to protect the lives of around 2,000 students present in the school at the time of the explosion.” Sources:  “Pakistan father hails teenage son Aitzaz Hassan who died while tackling suicide bomber.” AFP. 10 January 2014.  “Aitzaz Hasan: Tributes to Pakistan teenager killed when he stopped a bomber.” BBC 9 January 2014. “Hangu suicide blast.” The Express Tribune. 7 January 201 .

item.title: Bad time to be a pediatrician
item.description: I’m a pediatrician. Every day, I fight for kids to get what they need to be healthy, including vaccines. I feel so utterly beat down having to go head to head with the FEDERAL GOVERNMENT, who is simultaneously sowing doubt about the legitimacy of what we do and then using that doubt to suggest that our clinical practices haven’t been studied rigorously enough and need to be reconsidered. This fear mongering has already tangibly reduced vaccination rates and caused preventable pediatric deaths. These new updates will only worsen the situation. I have never felt so fucking demoralized and I just don’t want to do it anymore.

item.title: Things seen this week during structural assessments!
item.description:
Teeter-totter but make it structural. ? Post-and-pier foundations should be supported by solid footings and stable, well-compacted soil. Proper soil bearing capacity is essential to prevent settling, shifting, or structural damage over time. Regular inspections can help ensure the foundation remains stable and secure.
This three-story property is experiencing outward pressure due to soil movement. Many hillside homes have larger crawlspaces because they are built on slopes. In this case, the soil inside the crawlspace has shifted and is pressing against the cripple wall, creating significant lateral pressure on the structure.
Our team started work and opened up the area, revealing the damage the soil pressure has caused to the cripple wall and joists. We arrived just in time because this would not have lasted much longer without intervention.
We immediately installed emergency shoring to the area. Before any permanent repairs happen, unstable structures need to be stabilized so movement stops, loads are supported, and the home can be made safe while engineering and repairs move forward. ?
During the storm, hillsides across SoCal became saturated with water, causing them to lose stability. We saw this on our way to another appointment, and fortunately, no person or property was harmed. This is why it is important to make sure hillsides are properly secured or tarped during storms to prevent damage.
This 100-year-old balcony is slowly deteriorating, caused by age and exacerbated by improper drainage. When water cannot escape, it gradually breaks down the wood fibers, reducing the balcony’s strength until it can no longer safely support the weight it was designed to carry.
When moisture reaches the steel rebar embedded in structural concrete, it causes corrosion. As the steel expands, it forces the concrete to crack and flake off, a process known as spalling, which in turn causes the structural components to deteriorate.
Hillside properties and rain do not often mix, but preparation is key. Early preparation is essential to protect hillside properties from failure. Winterization measures, such as tarping and monitoring drainage, can help reduce erosion and minimize damage.
This deck framing has lost its structural integrity because moisture and rot have weakened the beams and deck that hold it up. Even if the surface looks okay, the load-bearing members underneath are no longer reliable, which is why replacement is the safest option. ☝️
This close-up shows exposed rebar and concrete breaking apart at the base of the structure. Once reinforcement steel is exposed, the footing is already deteriorating, which leads to loss of support and uneven settling of the structure above. ?
